The start symbol S has exactly one production:

S → NT104 NT26  

For the two‑token string “t5 t17” to be generated, we would need

NT104 ⇒ “t5” and NT26 ⇒ “t17”.

Looking at all terminal productions in the grammar:

• NT104 can only produce the terminals t15, t0, t13, or t28 (and can also expand to two non‑terminals, giving at least two terminals in total). It never produces t5.

• NT26 can produce t6, t0, or t14, or expand to “NT108 NT5”, but nowhere does it yield t17.

Since NT104 cannot produce t5 and NT26 cannot produce t17, no derivation from S can yield the string “t5 t17”.

Therefore the given grammar does not generate the string.

No

The start symbol is  
S → NT104 NT26.  
Hence the generated string must be the concatenation of a block produced by NT104 followed by a block produced by NT26.

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, the first terminal of the NT26‑block can only come from

• NT26 → 't6'  
• NT26 → 't0'  
• NT26 → 't14'  
• NT26 → NT108 NT5 with NT108 → 't1' | 't0' | 't7'

Thus the first token of the NT26 part must be one of  
t6, t0, t14, t1, t7.

Scanning the string

t28  t12  t15  t21  t27  t21  t3  t6  t15  t10  
t9   t18  t14  t20  t30  t17  t27  t18  t10  t1  
t4   t7   t14  t18  t2   t28  t16  t5   t9

the only positions where such a token occurs are

position 8 (t6), position 13 (t14), position 20 (t1),
position 22 (t7) and position 23 (t14).

For each of these five possible splits one has to check whether the suffix beginning at that
position can be derived from NT26.

• If the suffix starts with t6 or t14, NT26 would have to use its single‑terminal rule, so
it could generate only that one symbol, leaving the rest of the suffix unmatched – impossible.

• If the suffix starts with t1 or t7, NT26 must use NT26 → NT108 NT5 with NT108
producing that first symbol (t1 or t7).  
  In the t1‑case the remainder has to be derived
from NT5 and is 9 symbols long:  
  t4 t7 t14 t18 t2 t28 t16 t5 t9  
  In the t7‑case NT5 has to generate  
  t14 t18 t2 t28 t16 t5 t9.

  A detailed examination of every production of NT5 (it can only expand to
NT42 NT67, NT125 NT50, NT55 NT81, NT36 NT48 or NT38 NT39, or one terminal) shows
that none of its possible left children can produce a string whose first
terminal is t4 or t14 respectively. Consequently NT5 cannot begin with the
required symbol, so both splits fail.

Since every theoretically possible start position for the NT26 block has been
eliminated, no decomposition
string = (string produced by NT104)(string produced by NT26) exists.
Therefore the given string cannot be derived from the grammar.

No
